In addition, we looked into how the fluorescentlifetime of COL-CDchanged during the interaction of L-Adr process. As shown in Fig. 6D, the lifetime of COL-CDs (6.76 ns) was reduced to 4.43 ns after interacting with L-Adr (Table 1
                        ). Reduced in the fluorescence life time shows that PET mechanism with dynamic fluorescence quenching occurred. The interaction between the quencher L-Adr and the COL-CDs fluorophore is the cause for the decrease in the COL-CDs fluorescence intensity [43,44]. Furthermore, the L-Adr secondary amine group allows the electron to form intermolecular hydrogen bonds with the carboxyl and hydroxyl (–OH and –COOH) groups on the COL-CDs surfaces. Thus, excited electrons transported from L-Adr to COL-CDs that result in PET effect and fluorescence quenching of COL-CDs (Scheme 2
                        ).
